column18:
University of Wisconsin-Madison researchers are asking you to take part in a study called “LLM Causal Reasoning Discovery Procedure”.

You are invited to participate in a research study about how reasoning abilities are different in humans and large language models like chat-GPT. 



If you decide to participate in this research, you will be asked to generate some statements and imagine some different scenarios based on directions you will see. Failing to follow instructions may result in a denial of payment.



Your participation will last approximately 15-30 minutes (exact time as indicated in task description).

      

More detailed instructions will be provided on the next screen.



You will be compensated as stated in the task-info screen.

This task has no direct benefits. We do not anticipate any psychosocial risks. There is a risk of a confidentiality breach. The responses you submit as part of this task will be stored on a secure server and accessible only to researchers who have been approved by UW-Madison. Processed data with all identifiers removed could be used for future research studies or distributed to another investigator for future research studies without additional informed consent from the subject or the legally authorized representative.



You are free to decline to participate, to end participation at any time for any reason. We will not retain data from partial responses. If you would like to withdraw your data after participating, you may send an email lupyan@wisc.edu or complete this form which will allow you to make a request anonymously.



If you have any questions or concerns about this task please contact the principal investigator: Prof. Gary Lupyan at lupyan@wisc.edu.



If you have concerns about your rights as a research participant or have complaints about the research study or study team, call the confidential research compliance line at 1-833-652-2506. UW Staff not part of the study team will work with you to address concerns and assist in resolving any complaints.
column19:
University of Wisconsin - Madison

Research Participant Information and Consent Form

        

Study Title: Discovery Procedure for Causal Reasoning in LLMs

Principal Investigator: Gary Lupyan (Phone: (608) 262-4333) (Email: lupyan@wisc.edu)


Description of the research

You are invited to participate in a research study about how reasoning abilities are different in humans and large language models like chat-GPT. 



The purpose of the research is to understand how what differences exist in different kinds of causal reasoning between humans and large language models.



This study will include English-speaking adults from the psychology department participant pool.



This research will be conducted online.

        

What will my participation involve?
If you decide to participate in this research, you will be asked to generate some statements and imagine some different scenarios based on directions you will see. 

Your participation will last approximately 15-30 minutes.

       

Recording information

The experimenter will notify you if the specific task you are doing includes recording of your voice. Any audio recordings will be accessible only to approved research personnel or may be transcribed by a professional transcription service. The recordings will be kept indefinitely and stored on a secure server.

        

Are there any risks to me?

There is a risk of a confidentiality breach. Participants may become upset or experience discomfort. Participants may become fatigued or frustrated due to the length of the study.

        

Are there any benefits to me?

You are not expected to benefit directly from participating in this study.

        

Will I be compensated for my participation?

You will receive research study credit appropriate to the length of the study: 3 points per hour in increments of ¾ points).

         

 



How will my confidentiality be protected?

This study is confidential. Neither your name or any other identifiable information will be published. Raw data will be made available to research personnel approved as part of this protocol. De-identified data will be posted on open science repositories.



If you participate in this study, we would like to be able to quote you directly without using your name. If you agree to allow us to quote you in publications, please initial the statement at the bottom of this form.

        

Whom should I contact if I have questions?

You may ask any questions about the research at any time. If you have questions, concerns, or complaints, or think that participating in the research has hurt you, talk to the research team or contact the Principal Investigator Gary Lupyan at (608) 262-4333.

        

If you have concerns about your rights as a research participant or have complaints about the research study or study team, call the confidential research compliance line at 1-833-652-2506. UW Staff not part of the study team will work with you to address concerns and assist in resolving any complaints.

        

If you decide not to participate or to withdraw from the study, you may do so without penalty.

column66: The situation is so bad with ChatGPT in particular, that it now often gets basic math questions wrong. This is because of a phenomenon called “AI Drift” and it happens when a part of a complex AI model, ends up negatively affecting a different part.
column67: The list of ChatGPT competitors includes generative AI chatbots from industry giants like Google (Gemini), Microsoft (Bing Chat), Meta (Llama 2), and Amazon (Codewhisperer).
